Jamaica has put a cap on its3.5 billion dlr foreign debt and will reduce its obligations by300 mln dlrs this year, Prime Minister Edward Seaga said.    Seaga yesterday said Jamaica has reached its "maximum stockof debt" and will not undertake any more borrowing until it wasjustified by economic growth. "This year we'll be reducing thestock of debt by 300 mln dlrs," he said.    He said his government aims to get Jamaica's ratio of debtpayments to foreign exchange earnings down from the currentlevel of 50 pct to 25 pct over the next two to three years.Debt payments this year are expected to total 287 mln dlrs,Seaga said. Seaga yesterday concluded an agreement withJamaica's creditor banks to reschedule some 181 mln dlrs due in1987-89 over the next 12 years. Reuter&#3;